ccused of stealing a role that should have gone to a transgender actor. The video shows a petition demanding his removal from the play. Hugh expresses his devastation and the hateful messages he received. He reveals that he attempted suicide twice.\n\nThe video then shows Hugh sitting in a theater with his sister, Zoe. She describes the pain he was in and the targeted attacks he faced. Hugh confirms that he attempted suicide twice and expresses his shock at the accusations of transphobia. He explains that he didn't understand what he had done wrong.\n\nThe scene cuts to two men standing in front of a poster for \"Hedwig and the Angry Inch.\" One of the men is wearing glasses. The video then shows Hugh standing in front of some equipment cases, looking thoughtful. He discusses the cancellation of the play and the viciousness of the attacks. He expresses his regret that the production didn't stand by him.\n\nThe video returns to Hugh sitting with his sister. He talks about how the experience changed him and how he felt like he was in total shock. He mentions that he didn't want to put his family through the ordeal.\n\nThe video shows a montage of photos and videos of Hugh throughout his life, including childhood photos and clips from his career. He discusses his early love of acting and how he was discouraged from pursuing it by his school. He mentions that he was called out by the principal in primary school for not being normal.\n\nThe video concludes with Hugh running along a path near the Sydney Opera House. He talks about how he's fitter than ever and working harder than ever in a job he cherishes. He reflects on the challenges he's faced and how he's overcome them.",
